Children.Text:
The APSIM wheat model has been developed using the Plant Modelling Framework (PMF) of [#brown_plant_2014]. This new framework provides a library of plant organ and process submodels that can be coupled, at runtime, to construct a model in much the same way that models can be coupled to construct a simulation. This means that dynamic composition of lower level process and organ classes (e.g. photosynthesis, leaf) into larger constructions (e.g. maize, wheat, sorghum) can be achieved by the model developer without additional coding.

The wheat model consists of:

* a phenology model to simulate development through sequential developmental phases  
* a structure model to simulate plant morphology 
* a collection of organs to simulate the various plant parts  
* an arbitrator to allocate resources (N, biomass) to the various plant organs  

This work builds upon earlier APSIM Wheat models such as NWheat ([#Asseng200225], [#KeatingNWheat]), NWheatS ([#Asseng1998163]), Cropmod-Wheat ([#Wang2002GenericCropModel]), and the earlier versions developed in Plant ([APSIM Wheat 7.5](https://\"http://www.apsim.info/Documentation/Model,CropandSoil/CropModuleDocumentation/Wheat.aspx)") and then within the Plant Modelling Framework ([#brown_plant_2014]).

Children.Text:
The wheat models outputs of phase names (Phenology.CurrentPhase.Name), stage names (Phenology.CurrentStageName) and decimal stage (Phenology.Stage) are consistent with the population culm development score (PCSD) as described by [#Celestina2023]. 
Observations recorded following the protocole outlined by [#Celestina2023] are suitable for testing model accuracy and calibrating cultivar coefficients.

Wheat exhibits a range of developmental responses to environment and these are strongly influenced by genotype characteristics. 
Temperature is the primary driver of development, increasing development rates and decreasing phase durations as it increases.  These affects are captured by thermal time.  However, wheat also exhibits cold and photoperiod sensitivities in its Vernalisaing phase and further photoperiod sensitivity in the SpikeletDifferenation and HeadEmergence phases.  Photoperiod responses are seen as a reduction in the length of a phase for a photoperiod sensitive genotype in response to a longer photoperiod.  Vernalisation responses are more complicated as they are driven by cool temperature but interact with photoperiod.  For vernalisation sensitive varieties (Winter types), exposure to cool temperatures and/or short photoperiods during the Vernalising phase may reduce its thermal time duration.  

APSIM wheat implements the Cereal Anthesis Molecular Phenology ([CAMP](https://www.apsim.info/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/camp-model-description-1.pdf)) model to simulate development.  It is based on the Kirby Framework which assumes the timing of anthesis is a result of the timing of flag leaf and an additional thermal time passage from there to heading then anthesis.  It also assumes the timing of flag leaf is a result of the Final Leaf Number (which sets a target) and leaf appearance rate (which sets the rate of progress toward the target).  Leaf appearance rate is a function of Thermal time and a genotype specific Phyllochron which changes with Haun stage as described by [#Jamieson_LeafAppearance_1995].  

Final Leaf Number (FLN) is set on the day that terminal spikelet occurs as: 

FLN = 2.85 + 1.1 * TSHS  

Where TSHS is the Haun stage on the day terminal spikelet stage occurs.  Terminal spikelet is at the end of the SpikeletDifferentaiation phase which is preceeded by the Emerging and Vernalising phases.  The mechanisums for progress through each of these phase are described below

Children.Text:
Progress through the vernalising phase is determined by the apparent expression of Vrn1 and Vrn2 genes.  The CAMP model predicts the expression of these two genes.  
Vrn1 is the gene that orchestrates cold temperature responses in development.  To complete the vernalising stage firstly apparent Vrn1 expression must reach a value of at least 1.0.  In warm temperatures (>18oC), Vrn1 is expressed at a base rate that is genotype dependent.  This base rate is lower for vernalisation sensitive genotypes which will develop slower in the warm.  Vrn1 expression (relative to Haun stage increment) increases as temperature decreases so exposure to cold conditions will cause vernalisation sensitive varieties to develop faster (i.e. reach vernalisation at a lower Haun stage).  Vrn2 is up-regulated by longer photoperiods.  It blocks the expression of Vrn3 (which is required for progression through the spikelet differentiation phase) and must be down regulated completely before the vernalising phase is complete.  Vrn1 blocks Vrn2 expression so in effect the expression of Vrn2 raises the target for Vrn1 expression above 1.0.  The longer the photoperiod the greater the target increase so exposure to short days will reduce the target and length of the vernalising phase, a phenomena some times called short day vernalisation.  Vrn3 may also be active and accelerate the expression of Vrn1 during the vernalisation phase.  This effect is currently captured by VrnX in CAMP.  
The duration of the vernalising phase will be the result of a complex interaction between temperature, photoperiod and the genotypes tendency to express Vrn1 at warm temperatures (baseDeltaVrn1) and Vrn2 and Vrn3 under long photoperiods (MaxDpVrn2, MaxDVrnX).  These three rates are derived internally by the CAMP model from the genotypes FLNparams.
Children.Name: Memo

Children.Text:
Progress through the Spike differentiation phase is determined by the apparent expression of Vrn3 as predicted by CAMP.  
Vrn3 is a photoperiod sensitive gene that promotes expression of Vrn1.  Vrn1 is not able to express to adequate levels to achieve reproductive transition without Vrn3 upregulation.   Here we assume an apparent Vrn3 expression of 1.0 is sufficient to upregulate Vrn1 enough to trigger terminal spikelet.  
 Each genotype has a base rate of Vrn3 expression (baseDVrn3) at low photoperiods and a maximum rate of Vrn3 expression (maxDVrn3) under long photoperiods.  These two rates are derived internally by the CAMP model from the genotypes FLNparams.

Children.Text:
The CAMP model was derived to integrate molecular and physiological models of cereal flowering time to better capture G x E x M interactions and to provide a framework for linking genetic data to field behaviour.  It calculates the current levels of expression of Vrn1, 2 and 3 genes from daily deltas that are all calculated relative to haun stage deltas in addition to temperature (Vrn1) and photoperiod (Vrn 2 and 3).  To reach the vernalisation stage Vrn1 must be upregulated to a value of at least 1.0.  Where Vrn2 is also being expressed the target for Vrn1 expression increases in parallel as more Vrn1 expression is needed to block Vrn2 and allow Vrn3 expression.  Once Vrn2 expression is blocked Vrn3 will be upregulated and terminal spikelet occurs when its apparent expression reaches 1.0.  CAMP also predicts expression of VrnX which represents the relative contributions of Vrn2 and Vrn3 prior to vernalisation.  The genotype specific rates of gene expression are derived from final leaf number parameters (FLNparams):  

MinLN - The final leaf number (FLN) of the genotype when fully vernalised early and grown under long (>=16) photoperiod following vernalisation (FLN_LV).  These conditions maximise the expression of vernalisation and photoperiod genes and this parameter provides a measure of inherent earliness of the genotype. It may vary between 5 and 15 leaves (7 is typical).  

PpLN - The difference between MinLN and the FLN of a genotype when fully vernalised early and grown under short (<=8h) photoperiod following vernalisation (FLN_SV).  These conditions maximise Vrn1 expression but minimise Vrn2 and 3 expression and PpLN provides a measure of photoperiod sensitivity of the genotype.  It may vary between 0 and 8 leaves with 1 being typical of a low sensitivity genotype and 4 being typical of a high sensitivity genotype.  

VrnLN - The difference between MinLN and the FLN  PpLN of the genotype when not vernalised and grown under short photoperiod (FLN_SN).  These conditions minimise Vrn and Pp gene expression to base (minimal) values and VrnLN is a measure of vernalisation sensitivity of the genotype.  It may vary between 0 and 9 leaves with 1 being typical for an insensitive variety and 5 being typical for a sensitive variety.  

VxPLN - The difference between MinLN + VrnLN and the FLN of the genotype when not vernalised and grown under long photoperiod (FLN_LN).  These conditions minimise upregulation of Vrn1 and maximise upregulation of Vrn2 and 3 and this parameter provides a measure of the relative activities of Vrn2 and Vrn3 during the vernalisation phase. A positive value shows short days accelerate vernalisation and a negative value shows short days slow vernalisation.  The value of VxPLN should be greater than the negative of VrnLN and typically varies between +2 and -4.

Children.Text:
**Grain Number**

Grain number is calculated using the simple approach applied in earlier versions of the APSIM Wheat models where grain number is calculated directly from the mass of stem and spike atnthesis.  The parameter describing the potential number of grains per gram of the combined mass of stem and spike is commonly used as a cultivar-specific trait, often in concert with parameters for potential grain size.

```
GrainNumber = GrainsPerGrainStemPlusSpike x StemPlusSpike.Wt
```

where
 
Name | Description | Units
-|-|-
GrainNumber | Grains per unit area | /m^2^
StemPlusSpike.Wt | Mass of StemPlusSpike composite organ | g/m^2^
GrainsPerGrainStemPlusSpike | Number of grains per gram of mass in Stem + Spike | /g


**Grain Growth**

Grain growth occurs in two  phases (Expansion and Filling) with a specific growth rate applied to both to allow grains to reach their potential size by the end of grain filling.

```
GrainDMDemand = PotentialGrainGrowthRate x ThermalTime x GrainNumber

if in the GrainExpanding phenological phase
   PotentialGrainGrowthRate = PotentialGrainSize x InitialProportion / GrainExpanding.Target

else if in the GrainFilling phenological phase
   PotentialGrainGrowthRate = PotentialGrainSize x (1 -InitialProportion) / GrainFilling.Target

PotentialGrainGrowthRate = bound (PotentialGrainGrowthRate, 0, {PotentialGrainSize - GrainSize) x GrainNumber

```

where

Name | Description | Units
-|-|-
PotentialGrainGrowthRate | Potential daily increase in mean grain size | g/(^o^C.d)
ThermalTime | Daily thermal time increment calculated by the phenology model | ^o^C.d
PotentialGrainSize | Grain size achievable by the plant under optimal growing conditions | g
InitialProportion | Proportion of the PotentialGrainSize that is achieved by the end of the grain expansion phase | 0-1
GrainExpanding.Target | Thermal time duration of the grain expansion phase | ^o^C.d
GrainFilling.Target | Thermal time duration of the grain filling phase | ^o^C.d


**Grain Nitrogen Accumulation**

The accumulation of nitrogen within the grain occurs in a single phase including both the grain expansion and filling phases.  Again, this is calculated from a specific grain N accumulation rate as described below.  Note also that the daily N demand is limited to ensure that N accumulation is slowed when grain growth is slowed.  The later is achieved by ensuring a maximum N concentration of daily grain growth.  Finally, all dry matter and Nitrogen within the grain organ is assumed to be "structural", such that N cannot be retranslocated from grain and a minimum amount of N is required for any dry matter to be allocated to grain by the organ arbitrator.

```
PotentialGrainNAccumulationRate = PotentialGrainKernalN / (GrainExpanding.Target + GrainFilling.Target)
GrainNDemand = PotentialGrainNAccumulationRate x ThermalTime x GrainNumber
GrainNDemand = min (GrainNDemand, MaximumNConc x GrainDMDemand)

```

where

Name | Description | Units
-|-|-
PotentialGrainNAccumulationRate | Potential daily increase in grain kernal N content | g N/(^o^C.d)
PotentialGrainKernalN | Grain kernal N content under optimum growing conditions| g N
MaximumNConc | Maximum N concentration of daily growth (ie ratio of daily N and DM demand) | g N/g

Children.Text: Potential branching rate is determined by the commonly observed pattern of tillering in wheat, in which each tiller emerges with the third leaf on its parent axis (e.g. first tiller emerges at the same time as the third leaf on the main stem, the first secondary tiller appears with the third leaf on tiller 1).  This is described as a simple function of main stem leaf number.

Children.Text: **Canopy Development** Calculations are as follows: ``` Area = InitialArea + AccumulatedChange InitialArea = AreaPerPlant x Population AccumulatedChange = AreaGrowth - AreaSenesced - AreaRemoved - AreaShrinkage If current growth stage is between emergence and flagleaf AreaGrowth = AreaGrowth + SpecificLeafArea x Allocated.StructuralWt If current growth stage is between emergence and HarvestRipe AreaSenesced = AreaSenesced + SpecificLeafAreaCanopy x Senesced.StructuralWt If current growth stage is between emergence and flagleaf AreaRemoved = AreaRemoved + SpecificLeafAreaCanopy x Removed.StructuralWt If current growth stage is between flagleaf and anthesis AreaShrinkage = AreaSrhinkage SpecificLeafAreaCanopy x Live.StructuralWt x 0.2 x ThermalTime/TTFlagLeafToAnthesis ``` where Name | Description | Units -|-|- Area | Green leaf area per unit ground area | m2/m2 InitialArea | Leaf area of an individual plant at emerence | m2 AreaGrowth | Accumulated leaf area growth from emergence to flag leaf | m2/m2 AreaSenesced | Accumulated leaf area senescence from emergence to harvest ripe | m2/m2 AreaRemoved | Accumulated leaf area removed (e.g. grazing) from emergence to harvest ripe| m2/m2 AreaShrinkage | Accumulated leaf area reduction due to leaf shrinkage from flag leaf to anthesis| m2/m2 SpecificLeafArea | Area per unit mass of green leaf for today's leaf growth | m2/g SpecificLeafAreaCanopy | Area per unit mass of green leaf currently in the entire crop canopy | m2/g Allocated.StructuralWt | Mass of dm allocated to the leaf from daily growth by the organ arbitrator. | g/m2 Senesced.StructuralWt | Mass of live dm senesced on the current day. | g/m2 Removed.StructuralWt | Mass of live dm removed on the current day. | g/m2 ThermalTime | Daily thermal time calculated by the phenology model | oC TTFlagLeafToAnthesis | Thermal time target for the period from Flag leaf to Anthesis | oC **Potential Leaf Growth** Potential growth in leaf area is used to calculate the leaf dry matter demand. The potential increase in leaf area is calculated with estimates of leaf appearance, stem dynamics and plant population. The appearance and sizes of leaves are assumed to be similar on all stems. Leaf size is assumed to increase from emergence to the beginning of stem elongation. Leaf appearance is calculated within the Phenology model as part of the CAMP model. Note that leaf biomass is assumed to consist of entirely structural dry matter. Calculations are as follows: ``` if in vegetative phase (ie Emergence to Flag Leaf) DMDemand.Structural.Wt = deltaLAIPotential x SpecificLeafArea else DMDemand.Structural.Wt = 0.0 DMDemand.Storage.Wt = 0.0 DMDemand.Metabolic.Wt = 0.0 DeltaLAIPotential = AreaLargestLeaf x RelativeArea x Population x StemNumberPerPlant x LAR x ExpansionStressFactor LAR = ThermalTime / Phyllochron ``` where Name | Description | Units -|-|- DMDemand.Structural.Wt | Daily potential leaf structural growth (ie daily DMD demand for leaf growth) | g/m2 deltaLAIPotential | Daily potential increase in LAI if DM supply from arbitrator is adequate | m2/m2/d AreaLargestLeaf | The area of the largest leaf on the main stem. | m2 RelativeArea | The size of the currently expanding leaf compared to the largest leaf on the main stem | 0-1 StemNumberPerPlant | The number of currently expanding stems on each plant. | /plant LAR | The Leaf Appearance Rate, or the number of leaves appearing on the current day. | /day ThermalTime | Daily thermal time calculated by the phenology model | oC Phyllochron | The thermal time required for the appearance of each leaf on the main stem. | oC **Tiller Dynamics** The number of stems on each plant is calculated by adding an accumulation of the daily tillering rate to the main stem. Tillering rate is driven by main stem leaf number to account for the appearance of the main stem tillers with each main stem leaf after leaf three and each higher order tiller after the third leaf on each sub-tiller. Tillering will occur at optimum rates whilst canopy cover is less than 20% and cease once cover is above 80%. Calculations are as follows: ``` StemNumberPerPlant = 1.0 + TillerNumber - DeadTillerNumber TillerNumber = sum of (DeltaHS x TilleringRate) from Emergence to MaximumSpikeletPrimordia TilleringRate = PotentialTilleringRate x min(ExpansionStress, CoverEffect) DeadTillerNumber = sum of (TillerNumber x TillerAttritionRate) from MaximumSpikeletPrimordia to MaximumGrainLength TillerAttritionRate = function returning zero when GrowthRatePerTiller is above 0.03, increasing to 0.03/d when GrowthRatePerTiller is zero. GrowthRatePerTiller = five day moving average of (DailyGrowth / ThermalTime / StemPopulation ``` where Name | Description | Units -|-|- StemNumberPerPlant | Total number of stems on each plant (main stem and tillers) | /plant TillerNumber | Total number of tillers on each plant (including first, second, third,... order tillers. | /plant DeadTillerNumber | Number of dead tillers on each plant | /plant TilleringRate | Number of tillers appearing anywhere on the plant during the current day | /day PotentialTilleringRate | Potential number of tillers that could appear today in the absence of limiting factors| /day ExpansionStress | Rate modifier accounting for the effect of water, nitrogen or temperature. | 0-1 TillerAttritionRate | Proportion of live stems dying on the current day | /d CoverEffect | Rate modifier accounting for the effect of shading on tiller appearance. | 0-1 StemPopulation | Number of stems per unit area | /m2 GrowthRatePerTiller | Expression of daily growth rate relative to thermal time and tiller number | g/oC.d **Specific Green Leaf Area** The winter cereal model estimates the specific leaf area of daily leaf growth directly rather than as an emergent property of separaete area and mass growth functions as used in many earlier APSIM wheat models. An optimal SpecificLeafArea is reduced below 15C to a factor of 50% at a mean daily temperature of 5C. A WaterTensionFactor (provided by the Root Model) is used to capture effects of low leaf water potential on SpecificLeafArea and this will reduce SpecificLeafArea by 50% at a WaterTensionFactor of 0.8. These will result in a maximum reduction in SpecificLeafArea of 50% of the optimum value under either water or temperature limitation. ``` SpecificLeafArea = PotentialSpecificLeafArea x min (SWFactor, TemperatureFactor) ``` where Name | Description | Units -|-|- SpecificLeafArea | Area per unit mass of green leaf for today's leaf growth | m2/g PotentialSpecificLeafArea | SpecificLeafArea for daily leaf growth under optimal growing conditions | m2/g SWFactor | Water Factor to reduce SpecificLeafArea under water limiting conditions | 0-1 TemperatureFactor | Water Factor to reduce SpecificLeafArea under low temperature conditions | 0-1 **Canopy Light Extinction Coefficients** Canopy light interception is calculated by the methods described above using light extinction coefficients. The extinction coefficient for green leaf is assumed to change with plant growth stage and row spacing. The extinction coefficient is assumed to have a higher value up until DoubleRidge growth stage with leaves on small plants often falling more horizontally for this early growth. This initial value is a function of row spacing with a value of 0.9 at row spacing up to 150mm, decreasing to 0.7 at 500mm row spacing. Extinction coefficient then falls to a lower, stable (and row spacing independant) value once crops reach flag leaf stage. ``` ExtinctionCoefficient = LateVegetativeValue + (EarlyGrowthValue - LateVegetativeVale) x DevelopmentFactor ``` where Name | Description | Units -|-|- ExtinctionCoefficient | Daily light extinction coefficient for green leaf area for the current day | - LateVegetativeValue | The value of daily lignt extinction coefficient for canopies after flag leaf stage | - EarlyGrowthValue | The value of daily light extinction coefficient for canopies prior to double ridge | - DevelopmentFactor | A function to scale daily light extinction coefficient between double ridge and flag leaf stages | -

Children.Text: This is calculated to represent the supply of asslimilate to individual tillers over the past 5 days to use as an index to determine tiller mortality.  When tiller numbers are high or total crop assimilate supply is small there will not be enough assimilate to maintain all of the tillers so the model will senesce some.
